						               													<description>Battlefield is a Chinese Stratego rip-off, but with some differences.  For a start, each player has 44 pieces instead of 40.  There are half a dozen unit count differences, plus a different rank name.  Additionally, instead of lower rank number defining victory, the piece with the highest points wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Flag; 0 points, 1 piece&amp;#10;Marshal; 15 points, 1 piece&amp;#10;General; 10 points, 1 piece&amp;#10;Colonel; 9 points, 3 pieces&amp;#10;Major; 8 points, 4 pieces&amp;#10;Captain; 7 points, 5 pieces&amp;#10;Lieutenant; 6 points, 5 pieces&amp;#10;Sergeant; 5 points, 5 pieces&amp;#10;Miner; 4 points, 4 pieces&amp;#10;Soldier; 3 points, 9 pieces&amp;#10;Spy; 2 points, 1 piece&amp;#10;Bomb; 1 point, 5 pieces&amp;#10;&amp;#10;I'm yet to find any significant rules differences from Stratego.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game itself is &amp;quot;travel friendly&amp;quot;.  That is to say that it uses a plastic box where the lid flips over to reveal the playing board, though it's pushing the definition of &amp;quot;travel-sized&amp;quot;.  The instructions are on the back of the packaging.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;There are no credits or dates anywhere on the packaging or game, just &amp;quot;Made in China&amp;quot;.  It is apparently &amp;quot;Item No. 3313&amp;quot;.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
